erplay between presence and absence, movement and stillness: unlike death, killing entails the deliberate reduction of a singular subject to a disposable object. Like cinema, it involves a crucial choice about what to cut and what to keep.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDetective and mystery filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aMurder in mass media. 0aMurder in motion pictures. 0aThrillers (Motion pictures)xHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  afilm studies, movies, cinema, hollywood, violence, violent movie, imagination, literary scholarship, fictional works, fiction, form, murder, death, attacks, alfred hitchcock, humanity, humans, close ups, weapons, vsevolod pudovkin, guns, montage, lev kuleshov, andre bazin, jean renoir, loss, genre, stylization, stanley kubrick, cinematic representation, depictions of reality, interplay, killing, dying, motion picture, aesthetics, detective, mystery, suspense, thrillers, mass media.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022661794740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226617961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226617961/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles